@yajiedesign Thanks for reply, ImageRecordIter is fast and effective, but the iter still use one thread even if I set "preprocess_threads" to 4:
```
[19:15:22] D:\Program Files (x86)\Jenkins\workspace\mxnet\mxnet\src\io\iter_image_recordio_2.cc:153: ImageRecordIOParser2: E:/Projects/deeplearning/datasets/images/cifar10_mxnet/cifar10/cifar/train.rec, use 1 threads for decoding..
```
Then I check the mxnet source code, and find following code:
```C++
// src/io/iter_image_recordio_2.cc
  #pragma omp parallel
  {
    // be conservative, set number of real cores
    maxthread = std::max(omp_get_num_procs() / 2 - 1, 1);
  }
param_.preprocess_threads = std::min(maxthread, param_.preprocess_threads);
  #pragma omp parallel num_threads(param_.preprocess_threads)
  {
    threadget = omp_get_num_threads();
  }
  param_.preprocess_threads = threadget;
  if (param_.verbose) {
    LOG(INFO) << "ImageRecordIOParser2: " << param_.path_imgrec
              << ", use " << threadget << " threads for decoding..";
  }
// include/dmlc/omp.h
inline int omp_get_num_procs() __GOMP_NOTHROW { return 1; }
inline int omp_get_max_threads() __GOMP_NOTHROW { return 1; }
```
These code indicates that ImageRecordIter always use only one thread, "preprocess_threads" argument in ImageRecordIter is no use.

```C++
// include/dmlc/omp.h
inline int omp_get_num_procs() __GOMP_NOTHROW { return 1; }
inline int omp_get_max_threads() __GOMP_NOTHROW { return 1; }
```
only use when not openmp.but the my relase is use openmp.
